…as Ghana allocates 5% to Nigeria The demand for tickets by Nigerians resident in Ghana is on the increase, after the Ghana Football Association allotted five per cent of tickets for the match at the 40,653-capacity Baba Yara Stadium, Kumasi. Our correspondent learnt the GFA also assigned 1,000 VIP tickets to Nigerians on match-day March 25 for the potentially explosive clash. On Friday, Executive Committee member, Nigeria Football Federation, Aisha Falode, led an inspection team to the Baba Yara Stadium. In an exclusive interview with PUNCH Sports Extra, Falode stated that the Super Eagles will not lack fans support on Friday, adding that Nigerians have been demanding for tickets in their numbers. “On my arrival in the northern region, the Director of Sports in the region told me there’s been a high demand for tickets by Nigerians in Accra and Kumasi for the game,” Falode said. “I’m told 50 per cent of tickets for the 40,653-capacity Baba Yara Stadium has been allocated to Nigeria, plus an additional 1,000 VIP tickets. “So, we are also going to be there in our numbers. Even though the Ghanaians will be more, we will match them with our fan base on match day.”  Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com